Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 50th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
The Big 5-0.  Turns out that the world consistently produces enough optimis=
tic stuff each week that writing a weekly newsletter on the topic is actual=
ly quite easy.
It=E2=80=99s starting to feel like, at least amongst a certain set of influ=
ential people, that optimism is becoming the optimal strategy. It=E2=80=99s=
 in vogue to be optimistic. That=E2=80=99s certainly not because of this ne=
wsletter, but if we have played even a small role in that, then we=E2=80=99=
re closer to accomplishing our mission.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6PartnerHero [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/1819156f-3993-4941-8f5=
e-055d409c3035?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The key to growth is customer experience.
When Dan started Create, he spent 30+ hours per week answering CX tickets. =
Now, his CX is fully outsourced, which not only frees up hours each day but=
 also means he has a team fully dedicated to that area of the business. It=
=E2=80=99s a win-win.
What most founders come to realize is that CX isn=E2=80=99t a cost center. =
It=E2=80=99s a growth channel. Companies that invest in customer experience=
 early reduce churn, increase LTV, and drive more referrals. But building a=
 support team on your own can take a lot of time and money. That=E2=80=99s =
where PartnerHero [ https://substack.com/redirect/1819156f-3993-4941-8f5e-0=
55d409c3035?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] comes in.
PartnerHero [ https://substack.com/redirect/1819156f-3993-4941-8f5e-055d409=
c3035?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
builds high-quality, affordable, on-brand CX teams for incredible brands li=
ke Loom, Miro, Lovepop, Privy, Udemy, LMNT, and more. From solo founders li=
ke Dan to early stage startups to scaling businesses, PartnerHero has optio=
ns to fit your needs.
(1) How To Do Great Work [ https://substack.com/redirect/04b5b55c-1b45-420f=
-8b38-df4e0e5f5adb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]
By Paul Graham [ https://substack.com/redirect/fe0682f4-c5fc-4bef-b58a-52a6=
d8f14195?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]
There may be some jobs where it's an advantage to be cynical and pessimisti=
c, but if you want to do great work it's an advantage to be optimistic, eve=
n though that means you'll risk looking like a fool sometimes. There's an o=
ld tradition of doing the opposite. The Old Testament says it's better to k=
eep quiet lest you look like a fool. But that's advice for seeming smart. I=
f you actually want to discover new things, it's better to take the risk of=
 telling people your ideas.
Chances are that if you read The Weekly Dose of Optimism, you also came acr=
oss Paul Graham=E2=80=99s latest essay on Twitter or LinkedIn or elsewhere =
this week. When Paul Graham writes, our corner of the internet tends to rea=
d. And for good reason, Graham is the former founder or Viaweb and founder =
of Y-Combinator =E2=80=94 so when he writes about how to do great work, it=
=E2=80=99s probably going to contain some good nuggets in there.
The whole essay will take about 60 minutes to read and we encourage you to =
carve out some time this weekend to do it. We=E2=80=99re not going to share=
 the newsletter version of =E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s 10 game-changing insight=
s from Paul Graham=E2=80=99s latest essay=E2=80=9D but it basically comes d=
own to =E2=80=9Cfind a subject that you=E2=80=99re genuinely curious about =
and spend seemingly ridiculous amounts of time working and learning about t=
hat field.=E2=80=9D
One particularly interesting (and relevant) part of the essay was Graham=E2=
=80=99s reflection on pessimism. He concedes that, in some fields, it=E2=80=
=99s advantageous to be pessimistic, but if you want to do great work optim=
ism is an advantage.=20
Pessimists sound smart. Optimists do great work.
(2) US Weighs $1 Billion Hydrogen Demand Program to Boost Industry [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/e8eee8d2-ca0e-4a29-93cd-c0420a64d2f4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Daniel Moore [ https://substack.com/redirect/a27643f0-6157-4728-aee0-1d0a6f=
aeec62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for Bloomberg Law
The Energy Department would spend $1 billion to boost demand for clean hydr=
ogen under a new plan to provide initial revenue for the first large-scale =
producers and provide certainty for potential buyers.
The department plans to issue a notice of intent [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/21efcd0e-9e7e-45d7-ad4b-b61e5946e0ec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] Wednesday that explores an initiative =
to make demand-side commitments to hydrogen producers as part of its much-a=
nticipated $8 billion regional hydrogen hub program launched [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/a562593d-e4d2-4b07-b191-db966ad6a8f7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] last September.
The Department of Energy is looking to boost demand for clean hydrogen, whi=
ch is a small part of the Biden Administration=E2=80=99s plan to achieve ne=
t-zero greenhouse gas emissions across the US economy by 2050. The problem =
with hydrogen, as it currently stands, is that there isn=E2=80=99t a ton of=
 demand for it. And there isn=E2=80=99t a ton of demand for it because ener=
gy industry buyers are naturally conservative. Conservative, not in the pol=
itical sense, but in the =E2=80=9CNobody ever got fired for buying IBM=E2=
=80=9D meaning of the term.=20
So there=E2=80=99s no demand, and because there=E2=80=99s no demand, there=
=E2=80=99s no investment in hydrogen infrastructure, and because there=E2=
=80=99s no investment in infrastructure, the switch to hydrogen becomes a r=
iskier proposition for energy buyers, and these guys don=E2=80=99t want to =
take unnecessary risk=E2=80=A6and so on and so forth.
How to break this cycle? Inject $1B of government-backed demand into the sy=
stem to turn the vicious cycle into a positive flywheel. It=E2=80=99s like =
a government-scale version of Frontier=E2=80=99s advance market commitment =
to accelerate carbon removal [ https://substack.com/redirect/14c0add2-9aef-=
4ce7-86c8-9092cd8712db?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(3) Renewables are saving Texas. Again. So give them their due. [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/0bc002d7-eabd-4d3f-b09b-30d3895c436c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Catherine Rampell [ https://substack.com/redirect/e4f73ce2-f2bf-44b7-b387-2=
6fced112685?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for The Washington Post
Though not exactly known for its bleeding-heart-liberal populace, Texas gen=
erates more electricity from wind and solar [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/7180dd0a-50a5-40bf-934e-b3fecbfcc870?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] than any other state. Of the 710 megawatts =
of new battery storage that went online across the United States in the fir=
st three months of 2023, about 70 percent was in Texas alone, according to =
data from S&P Global [ https://substack.com/redirect/f2c0b6b9-070c-4b27-aef=
5-3619f3489081?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ].
Quick: name the state that=E2=80=99s leading the charge on renewable energy=
=2E
I bet Texas, the land of cowboy-hatted wildcatting oilmen, wasn=E2=80=99t t=
he first state that came to mind. But the Friendship State generates more e=
lectricity from wind and solar than any other state, and contributed over 7=
0% of all new battery storage capacity in the US this year.
This extra renewable energy has kept the lights on and the temperatures coo=
l (actually, not speaking in innuendo here) in the hellishly hot state, and=
 has likely saved state residents billions of dollar this year. So how did =
Texas, a state built on oil riches, find itself at the forefront of the ren=
ewable energy movement?
Well first, Texas is riding a much larger renewable wave. Federal incentive=
s. Declining cost curves. Better battery technologies. All the things we wr=
ite about in this newsletter that are driving the renewable energy movement=
=2E
But all states benefit from those changes, so why Texas? Landscape: Texas i=
s sunny and windy, the perfect combo for solar and wind energy production. =
Demographics: Texas is a growing state. More people demand more energy. The=
y need renewable energy capacity to stay online. And finally, permissive pe=
rmitting: Texas makes it easy to build. Whether it=E2=80=99s houses or new =
renewable energy projects, ain=E2=80=99t no government bureaucrat gonna tel=
l a Texan what he can or cannot build.
(4) California lawmakers OK Newsom's push to build energy, water and transp=
ortation projects faster [ https://substack.com/redirect/2d0730f0-f6e4-4cda=
-a77d-f0210cc6ffbc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashley Zavala [ https://substack.com/redirect/f5405a1d-42e9-4e69-8637-e087f=
ef4627b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for KCRA3
California lawmakers on Wednesday approved Gov. Gavin Newsom=E2=80=99s infr=
astructure package that aims to make it easier and faster to build renewabl=
e energy, water and transportation projects in the state. The package of bi=
lls aims to cut down on the process, paperwork and litigation time for infr=
astructure projects that are subject to California=E2=80=99s Environmental =
Quality Act.
If building fast is cool, consider California=E2=80=A6the least cool state =
ever. The state has=E2=80=A6built=E2=80=A6a reputation for pushed-back dead=
lines, missed budgets and regulatory nightmares. And for good reason =E2=80=
=94 the California High-Speed Rail is years behind schedule and billions ov=
er budget, there=E2=80=99s a major housing shortage driving up housing pric=
es, and basically any energy project knows it will be held up by CEQA (the =
California equivalent of NEPA) to the tune of millions in legal fees and ye=
ars of regulatory headache.
California has gotten away this for years, but Governor Newsom has determin=
ed that it=E2=80=99s now politically popular to cut some of that red tape. =
His new package, which was passed by the California State Senate on Wednesd=
ay, makes it easier to build renewable energy, water, and transportation pr=
ojects in the state.
This is a big win for California (assuming it actually leads to more effici=
ent building) and likely a big win for the environment at large. CEQA, whic=
h is meant to protect the California government, has killed or slowed down =
(intentionally or not) renewable energy projects for years.
(5) This futuristic entertainment venue in Las Vegas is the world=E2=80=99s=
 largest spherical structure [ https://substack.com/redirect/738ace64-5ec6-=
4ccf-a1d6-dddb0bfc37ca?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Brandon Griggs [ https://substack.com/redirect/45523450-6574-4513-a207-9c87=
967c7278?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for CNN
At 366 feet tall and 516 feet wide, it=E2=80=99s being billed as the world=
=E2=80=99s largest spherical structure. Its bowl-shaped theater reportedly =
contains the world=E2=80=99s highest-resolution wraparound LED screen. And =
its exterior is fitted with 1.2 million hockey puck-sized LEDs that can be =
programmed to flash dynamic imagery on a massive scale =E2=80=93 again, rep=
ortedly the world=E2=80=99s largest. It was fully illuminated for the first=
 time Tuesday night to celebrate the Fourth of July.
Speaking of building things, on Tuesday Las Vegas unveiled the world=E2=80=
=99s largest spherical structure to celebrate the 4th of July. The structur=
e, which stakes claim to a number of other =E2=80=9Cworld=E2=80=99s largest=
=E2=80=9D superlatives, is scheduled to become a mainstay of The Strip late=
st this year.
If we=E2=80=99re being honest, I have no idea why Las Vegas built this thin=
g. But as Tobi Lutke summarized on Twitter [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
3bf84b95-806d-4fc3-8eb5-97fe2f677b52?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CWe are builders and we need to bui=
ld.=E2=80=9D Whether it=E2=80=99s building high-utility energy infrastructu=
re in California or vanity LED spheres in Sin City, our country builds shit=
=2E Or at least, we should build=20=
shit. That=E2=80=99s when we=E2=80=99re at o=
ur best.
And speaking of being pumped up about these United States of America, we th=
ink Jamie Dimon puts it best in this video.
America holds the best hand ever dealt. Best economy. Best military. Best u=
niversities. Strong work ethic and innovation. Peaceful neighbors. Natural =
resources.
Let=E2=80=99s double down. Let=E2=80=99s build on that lead. U.S.A U.S.A U.=
S.A
P.S. He=E2=80=99s definitely running.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. Packy will be back on Tuesday. Have a gre=
at weekend!
Thanks for reading,
-Dan + Packy

